## ⏳ Waiting Without Blocking

In the web, fetching data from a database takes time. We can't freeze the whole browser while waiting. We use **Asynchronous** patterns.

---

## 1️⃣ The Call Stack & Event Loop

*   **Call Stack**: Executes your code line-by-line.
*   **Event Loop**: Handles tasks that take time (APIs, Timeouts) and "pushes" them back to the stack when ready.

---

## 2️⃣ Fetch & Promises

`fetch` is the built-in browser API to talk to servers. It returns a **Promise** (a value that will exist in the future).

```javascript
fetch('https://api.example.com/data')
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(data => console.log(data))
  .catch(error => console.error(error));
```

---

## 3️⃣ Async / Await: The Modern Way

Syntactic sugar to make async code look like synchronous code.

```javascript
async function getData() {
  try {
    const res = await fetch('...');
    const data = await res.json();
    console.log(data);
  } catch (err) {
    alert("Failed to load!");
  }
}
```

---

## ✅ Deliverable: Phase 1 Final Project
Using everything you've learned, fetch data from a public API (like JSONPlaceholder) and display it on a responsive, semantic HTML page styled with Tailwind CSS.
